[h1]Comments[/h1]

[b]Comments[/b] are explanatory statements that you can include in the C++ code to explain what the code is doing. 
The compiler ignores everything that appears in the comment, so none of that information shows in the result. 

A comment beginning with [b]two slashes (//) [/b]is called a single-line comment. The slashes tell the compiler to ignore everything that follows, until the end of the line. 

[b]For example:[/b] [code format="cpp" codeId="176"]#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
   [b]// prints "Hello world"[/b]
   cout << "Hello world!";
   return 0;
}[/code]
When the above code is compiled, it will ignore the [b]// prints "Hello world" [/b]statement[b] [/b]and will produce the following result: [img id="2403" width="100%"]
